segments.text: Then let the army do it.
You cannot run the battlefield from the White House.
I don't care who's president.
It's the big fancy word today is micromanagement.
We didn't know what it was then, but they were doing it.
That's not how you get there from here.
Give your units an assignment for which they're trained to do.
In wartime, things happen wrong and examples
You may get 50 Arabic linguists sent to a war in Vietnam because they finished language school and everybody's going to Vietnam.
Why, you learned Arabic and I learned Vietnamese, but sir, it took me two years to learn that one.
Learn this one, you got a year while you're here.
Start interrogations at 2 o'clock a day.
Hi, I'm down here.
You got any Arabs for me to interrogate?
These accidents happen.
The sheer numbers.
You try to get between the perfect and the imperfect.
There's some compromise out there.
Hopefully the ideal prevails a little bit.
Sometimes it doesn't.
On that train of thought, I've heard or it's been said that Vietnam, the war was managed rather than... Oh, yeah.
It was war by management.
And that's where the body counts, the ratio of management.
I can scale it.
and measure you.
Wars are won or lost on leadership.
That's the difference between the American units, even though the advisory program was management.
You were in the woods if the decision was wrong.
You were out there with their unit you were peddling your good expert advice to.
They may not just take it.
No, sir, we don't want any of that today.
Then you had to see if you were smart enough to get the same advice, figure out another way to get there.
It hangs on leaders.
It falls on leaders.
All wars do.
Never seen a manager win one yet.
So what do you think about the bombing, the effect that the American firepower had, in particular on the way that the South Vietnamese viewed
the U.S. troops in the United States?
How did it affect you, especially since you were working with MACV?
Well, where we were, where I was in MACV, we did not have, in III Corps, in Saigon, Benoit, Jardin, which was the west of, we were in Benoit.
We did not have this mass firepower of American units.
We were in the pacified region.
There was no effect on us.

uh you didn't see b-52 sorters you could see the planes go over uh one of the things is the vietnamese i think by us making them miniature copies relied on our technology artificially introduced into their system when we left we took our goodies with us you know if there was a problem in vietnam it wasn't the problem of how to fight even though there was a problem there
It wasn't a problem of should we fight.
I think if anybody sees an attack going on that we perceived, and I hope we were right, you get in.
The problem was the way we left.
If we're going to turn the war over to win for yourselves because we can't stand the pain any longer because too many of us are dying of being crippled.
Good luck, suckers.
And now the good news.
We're leaving.
The bad news is we're taking our toys with us.
The Toys R Us store was closed.
Weapons R Us quit being Weapons R Us.
We didn't supply the B-52s for them.
We couldn't supply that quality that was missing in the Army leadership.
It was missing in ours at the same time, possibly.
I think the outcome based on what we did to the Army was a foregone conclusion.
It was...
Senator Aiken from Vermont said, if you're going to leave, just leave.
Declare yourself a winner and come home.
We did.
Peace with honor.
Was there anything in particular that stands out in your mind as far as...
I know we talked about morale a little bit, but...
especially when you were working as an advisor, that had a very positive effect on the RFPF forces that you were utilizing?
Well, I think the biggest effect we had in that area was we retrained the NCO and others at the local level, at the district level.
sent some RF units through our own in-house training, scrounged up the extra ammo, the guns, the uniforms, ran them through what would amount to our boot camp.
Never mind the bull that goes with boot camp.
Run them through.
Everybody's already got a rifle.
Now they're all the same.
We want to show you what M16s can do.
Run them through it and see the morale difference in the unit.
Now they can get ammunition.
They've got all the weapons of the same.
They've got the best.
We're carrying them, but they're carrying them.
They got rid of the bolt-action rifle, the nine kinds of ammo, everybody looking like a rag muffin.
They looked like an army.
I think that was probably the biggest success a sergeant working down there with me ever did.
Run them through it.
We'd go out there, we'd run them through it.
He runs them through it.
I'm the officer.
I stand there with their officer and watch.
He runs them.
It's then going back in the village with them.
and seeing these units fight communists on a local level, act like an army.
Instead of acting like 20-year-old kids, 20-year-old men, 10-year-old dogs crippled up, old age, over the hill, they gained this togetherness.
Their equipment they knew was going to work.
We scroungers used magazines, and how we got them, you know, scrounging was a way of life.
When you were through training them, they looked good.
They acted better.
They were an army.
They weren't a collection.

And I would think if I had one thing I'd point a finger at and say, yes, there's something about an RFPF unit I can stick my fingers on, they looked like a military unit instead of a bunch of people out for weekend drill.
Uh, seriously, I kind of lost my train of thought.

the uh do you think that i know i noticed you mentioned a while ago that you felt like that at the hamlet level the rfp forces they were the key to our success or they would have should have been or could have been they were where we went in live with them work with them necessarily died with them they were the keys

because the village the hamlet in vietnam was that's the center of their universe not this abstraction called national government in saigon that's the french-american creation there was only one person known to everybody in vietnam was ho chi minh bao dai was well known also southerner
Once you got past that, it was the Vietnamese generals who were favored by the Americans, and if we didn't like you one day, we killed you off or replaced you in the next coup.
It's at the village, the Vietnamese, the graves, the ancestors are there.
Life evolved about spot X, Y, the village, the hamlet.
That's where you won the hearts and minds, if that's what we're going to talk about, winning in the war.
You convinced them to quit straddling the fence, and 80% of them sat on the metal and watched.
Let's get them off the fence.
Whoever gets them off the fence wins the war.
It didn't matter what happened in the jungle, what happened in the towns with the guns, the big army fights.
It's out there.
I'm winning them five at a time, ten at a time, or I'm losing them.
I saw a quote on a film.
I don't remember the name of it.
Westmoreland made the statement that the value of life to Asians was not, they didn't place as great a value on life as Westerners do.
What do you think about that statement?
Well, first, I think something you need to look at in a question like that, part of it's going to be a religious answer.
If you're a Buddhist,
You're coming back again and again and again until you obtain perfection.
Life's not one trip through.
The next thing is, if you're a communist commander and all you have is people to throw at our high-firepower technology, you throw a mass of people at it.
There was a difference in value there.
Not to say that we would not expend you for a target.
We did.
It's just that we don't hang signs on it and say, hey, dear Ms. Smith, we just spent Johnny and 24 of the men in an aerial recon scout platoon so we could find 1,000 communists and kill them.
We sent the scouts out, and your job in life was radio back and say, boss, we found them.
Give me your grid, quick.
That was your job in the war.
Did that happen?
Sure it happens.
You mean when you breathe?
There's no rescue.
You last 30 seconds.
The unit's still in the area.
We're not going to get out there with a thousand men to rescue you.
We sent you probing.
Johnny, it's take the stick and go poke in the woods and find me something.
When you find it, phone me.
Now, it's the intel types that try to guess what did you find.
Sir, I think they found the big one.
We better get out there.
And everybody piled on.
We were air mobile.
We could fly you from Bryan to here anywhere 10 miles, 20 miles, 30 miles, 40 miles rapidly.
But not rapidly enough to save that unit.
It just went out there.
But that's okay.
Look how we cover it.
The platoon was annihilated.
That was the usual case.
Or badly shot at, militarily unaffected.
But when you did the company back, it lost one out of four platoons.
It's ineffective.
The battalion lost one platoon out of 19, 20, however many was in a battalion.
The brigade lost one platoon out of its 50 platoons or 200.
The brigade didn't even miss them.
And that night on the 5 o'clock briefing, you were a pinpoint.
Yes, sir, we made contact with the enemy this morning.
It commenced at 0900, whatever time it started.
And we're piling on, sir.
The initial report was we lost 20 men killed.
We've now killed several hundred of them.
The fight continues.
It may take four, five, six days to play it out.
Somewhere along the way, the enemy starts to withdraw because you replied your superior firepower.
They're breaking off contact.
They're sneaking away.
A little carriage won't stand up and fight.
In about a week, it's all over with big battles.
And when you threw, nobody knows who that platoon was that disappeared.
They just gone.
Did they, when after the platoon made contact, did they call in the artillery immediately?
No, they didn't always have it.
They were sometimes in range, sometimes out of range, just depending where we sent you.
We want you to go look for it, boys.
What patrols do is go out there in those spots that aren't covered and look around.
What did you find?
We think there's 800 of them out there.
Go find them.
Now, you stir them up good, you hear.
Tippy, tippy, tippy, tippy, tippy, and then whack, you show up.
They had figured out pretty quickly all the places you could land helicopters in.
They had people watching them.
They watched them.
You tried to sneak in.
Sometimes you snuck in, sometimes you didn't.
They didn't want to shoot you.
The asshole laid flat and let you walk by them.
They want you dead, you're dead.
But we traded those people to get the big numbers.
I wouldn't think in some ways they were any worse callous or more callous than us.
I think there's a technology difference.
They had to employ more people.
I don't think any commander loves to throw away men.
You know, I don't think, and I think that's one of the things that I think we had a bad picture.
If you understood that you had five tries to do life or ten tries, you could play them differently.
You could learn something every time you come through.
If that's what they believe, then they can afford to be different.
Regardless of what's true, it's perception that counts.
And the problem we had is we had to write letters home to Mayor Smith.
Dear Mayor Smith, Johnny's not going to come back.
Johnny's on his way home early.
From what I saw on the TV when I would come back in Ashford looking at it, we ran the war scores on TV like a football game.
Them on one corner of the screen and us on the other.
I'm not sure what that said back here either, except the numbers got bigger every year.
You know, when you're over there, you don't know how many men died.
You knew how many men died in your local area, how many men was wounded.
You didn't have the war toes.
It wasn't your job to worry about it.
Then you come home and you find out, well, gosh, is this how it went?
Yeah, home.
And it's, so what?
What do you, how do you think that?
Or do you think the anti-war movement back in the States had an effect on the troops in Vietnam?
When you were there, did you realize it was going on?
You would hear in 67 and 68, yeah, we heard.
How much an effect it had, I'm not sure.
Some of the guys held up pictures of the protesters back home, you know, and poked holes through them so you can, you know,
Some came over less willing to die in a place that didn't look like it was going to win.
I think the demonstrations back home, from looking backward at it, was a turning point signal that the other side looked at and said, if the American public doesn't support the war, we've won.
It's hard to say which happens first.
Was the public here against the war when the numbers got too big, the expense got too high?
and we'd have left anyway, or was that extra shove what happened?
I don't know.
You know, still don't.
It happened.
It did have an effect.
In the advisory program, I don't think we paid much mind to it.
You know, you weren't into worrying about it.
Do you think that the National Guard should have been called up?
That decision, when Lyndon Johnson, having made the decision not to call the Guard, that settled it.
If there's a turning point in the war, militarily, in thinking, it's the decision not to disrupt the national economy by calling the Guard.
I personally believe if you have them, you should be able to use them.
You should also keep them trained for that use.
They weren't.
The Guard wasn't trained in that era.
It was the place to go if you didn't want to go.
The way to save your butt was join the Guard.
If there's ever a thought about that, and I'm going to put it in even though it's not in this era, did Quail avoid going?
He damn sure did.
And I think one of the cartoons on the wall was, had the wall saying, Dan Quail, where were you?
He was home saving his butt.
If he's a hawk, hawks go.
And I guess I class myself as a hawk, I went.
If you're a hawk, you eat chickens.
And leave it at that.
That's an out of context thing.
I had made my decisions.
I would.
I can't climb in anybody else and answer for them.
They have to answer for themselves.
How did you feel about the draft doctors?
Did that have any effect on you after you came back?
I recognize you have a right in our system not to go.
I also recognize you may choose to break a law and not go and go to jail and pay your price.
They didn't pay.
Personally, I don't like them, but I have to live with them, and they have to live with me.
So it's that conflict in American politics that's never going to be resolved.
The ones that want to go are going to go.
And think what they think about the ones that went, and then, you know, as it turns out, the ones that didn't go said, say we didn't win, so what were you and all your friends dying for?
And it's the unanswerable question.
I did not like what they did.
They have a right to do that.
You know, I'll defend their right to say no.
I don't have to like you for saying no.
That's right.
That's interesting.
And...
This is like the thing, and I had a medic that was a conscientious objector, one of the best guys I ever knew in my life.
Wouldn't carry a gun.
He served.
I didn't like him because he was a CO, and I make no whine about it, but he was a good man, one of the best I ever had.
He did his job.
Everybody warned me he was different.
Being different
Didn't kill him, didn't mark him, but I'm saying, you know, looking at it, why don't you carry a gun?
I don't believe in it.
Why are you here?
I didn't believe in running.
And you have to admire him.
I admire him much more than I admire the ones either hid in the Garden of States or tiptoed to Canada or Mexico or anywhere, or just hid.
You know, I guess I fired it with my last name, and irony that Stallone becomes famous with that name.
And at least I've been told that he was in a girls' school, a dance school in Switzerland.
Oh, really?
But, uh, but see, perception becomes reality.
And, uh, you know, it's one of those strange quirks.
Well, did you, do you think, uh,
I think selective service had to enforce a set of rules that had too many loopholes.
If asked, do you favor a draft, my answer is yes, but universal military conscription.
At age 18, everybody goes.
If you don't want to carry a rifle, I've got plenty of bedpans.
Plenty of national hospitals.
That way you don't have to wear a uniform and do one thing to help a war effort.
I am probably opposed to a volunteer army because I believe they are mercenaries, pure and simple, out for a paycheck.
And I prefer one of draftees.

Even with the problem of education of the draftee, I believe that's the only way you put your people as a group in touch with this side of democracy which says some of us may have to go die in order for the rest of us
to have what we consider the good life.
I don't think we should have it on just volunteers.
Of course, I recognize the law really says in Congress, if there's a war, we'll draft.
I think we should use a draft all the time.
It leaves you with a large professional manpower pool if you need it.
We're out of that manpower pool.
The guys from Vietnam are aged 35 to 40, 45, 50.
It's been nearly 20 years since the last large units left.
If you have to call up reserves, all you've got left now are the reservists, the guard units, the regular Army, and I'm going to call them the over 40 Vietnam guys.
You need a different force, I believe, than that to help.
And I think a draft is a way to keep new people entering the manpower pool in large numbers.
Do you think that the...

because of the the deformance and everything that there was a any particular segment of society that was well sure whittled down i think whether it's fair or unfair that is a matter of fact more blacks and browns and poor whites if you want to call them a disadvantage whatever good name you want to stick on poor or others
died.
You know, one of the problems with saying, well, it was just purely accidental, was we gave deferments.
If you had money to stay in college, you had the IQ.
But if you'd graduated in that era and didn't want to go to college, you were battlefield meat.
If you were poor, regardless of race, you became an infantryman, a mortarman, a rifleman, the grunt.
If you had the education, you became an intelligence, became an officer, became an NCO, something.

Also, it should be said at the same time, the people wanting out of the barrio, the ghetto, and off the street, they also volunteered to go to those elite units that drew extra pay because they wanted the money.
It was a ticket out.
A lot of those tickets got punched.
It was an out with a dead end.
Others got out.
And I personally think they paid disproportionately.
And that's why I would go back to the original answer, a universal.
No holes, no exceptions.
Then we don't have to worry about, why didn't you?
Won't be anybody.
It'll just be you and them or whatever.
When you came back to the States, did you have any particular feeling that stood out in your mind when you were confronted by the sentiment here?
Yeah, I would think, you know, you...
come back to the West Coast, go through the airports, find out the guys wearing the uniforms, the bad guys, the good guys were in the street with sticks, weren't the police either.
It was, and I guess the biggest resentment part was, it was the country kind of in a way said, God, we sent you, but we sure hate to acknowledge you were there.
And I think that was the, that's more damning and more aggravating
than whether some people in the street didn't like what you did.
You can live with them.
It's the official side of it, the non-recognition side.
Did you feel betrayed by the government?
I'm not sure I ever analyzed it up to that point.
You didn't have your homecoming parade, but it wasn't World War II either.
I think the longer it went, the longer you look back, the more it may have worked toward that.
I don't like that word.
I'm not sure that's the one I'd pick.
I'm not sure what I'd put in there.
Anger at the government probably didn't do more to solve its own problem of it was going to go win or go stay home.
I think long term, you look at the loss of the guys you worked with, and you're always going to have that question.
If it was a good cause, and we went.
They died and paid for a good cause.
If it was a bad cause, why did we go?
And I don't think anybody who went necessarily, and those in that area who didn't go, are going to be able to judge out with a good, clean answer on either side was it a good or bad cause.
I think it started out with some very noble ideals.
I think it evolved into something else.

and I'm not sure what I would do with it other than saying, I think, to go back that line, if we're going to go, then let's go win, because I think at the time I was in Vietnam, even in the advisory program, I viewed the war as winnable if.
Get up and do something.
Do you have any experiences on your return that stand out?
Anything where you treated?
Oh, I think everybody had a spot where you hit where were you, you know, and somebody said, oh, you were,
quote-unquote the baby killer, I think a lot of guys bumped into at least one of those.
I'm not sure it's any worse than the draft dodger who went to Canada coming back, and he was one of them.
I think every war has a high side and a low side.
You know, the parade down Main Street is one side of it.
And what do you say about your war?
You know, at least the first clear loss we suffered in quite a while.
You know, everybody used to remark, and I guess particularly the early days in ROTC in the early 60s, wonder what the German Army felt like that lost in World War II.
Now you know.
No.
You got your answer in the 70s.
It didn't kill the Army.
We went through an evolution of leadership.
I'm not sure of management back into leadership now.
I'm still not sure we've evolved out what picture we want the Americans to have.
When you borrow women from combat,
but let them take the jump slots and fly the planes in peacetime that the men will have to do in flying wartime.
I find that totally ironic.
I say if I can't use them, I don't want them wearing the jump wings.
I don't want them standing in the door of my plane.
If they can wear the wings and fly the planes and pull the trigger, then I want the law changed that says we're going to put them on the front line and treat them just like any other soldier.
You know, I think part of ours is to question ourselves of what we want society to be like.
Do you really want your women out there with you cutting throats?
See, we have these myths we have in our society.
The Tarzan and Jane, whatever you want to make it out to be.
Now we find out Jane's maybe a better killer than you are.
Do you think that it was a... that our failure in Vietnam was a product of those myths?
Do you think that our culture didn't allow us to win, or...
Or the myths that we went over there with caused us to not be able to?
Or the myths even got us there in the first place?
Well, I think the question we said in World War II was the strategic region of the country, of the world.
If it was, then it still is.
You're always conditioned by your perception of the world.
What is it?
We were conditioned.
We got there.
We had a set of beliefs that didn't fit reality.
We didn't adjust them.
In a way, Vietnam was to us what the end of the British Empire was to them, the ending of World War II.
The Empire slips away.
We did ours a little differently.
I think we didn't want territory as such, merely want control of the region.
I think you need to decide when you go

what's it worth how much will i will i pay how much am i willing to pay where do i draw the line if the line is to leave short of accomplishment of it then you should ask yourself should i go at all and i think that takes a look at reality that we still may not want to face and i think there's been a number of books written on the limits of american power it should be marked with american lives
I think you spend too many Americans in a war that isn't fought quickly, and I tell everybody, we like our wars like football games, four quick quarters and sudden overtime, if necessary.
But don't make it a forever affair.
You know, Vietnam, a 10,000-day war, the forever war.
The first policy war we fought, our policy is contained communism.
We've had it from Truman to Eisenhower, all of them.
In Vietnam, we got ourselves caught in the swamp.
We got bogged down and won.
Could we have won if we'd applied enough men or enough technology at the right time?
Sure.
Did we have the resolve to win?
No.
I think the resolve went to the crew that won.
Do you think that...
the myths that led us there in the first place were valid?
Or could we have even known if they weren't?
